Midterm Momentum

Can street mobilization be an electoral barometer?

Lowell Monis1

March 31, 2025

Midterm elections in the U.S. are often a referendum on the party in power, with the out-party typically gaining seats. But what happens when protest movementsspontaneous, ideologically charged, and highly visibledisrupt historical trends? The 2018 and 2022 midterms, followed by the 2020 and 2024 presidential cycles, offer a fascinating case study. While polls and economic indicators dominate electoral forecasting, protest activity provides a real-time pulse of the national mood, sometimes foreshadowing unexpected outcomes.

This analysis leverages protest data from the Crowd Counting Consortium (20172024) (Ulfelder (2025a), Ulfelder (2025b)) to argue that the valence (left/right lean) and focus of mass mobilization can override traditional midterm dynamics. Notably, while left-leaning protests have consistently outnumbered right-leaning ones since 2017, shifts in right-wing mobilization may signal electoral momentum for Republicans.

The Blue Wave

In 2018, the Democratic Party flipped 41 House seats, fueled by anti-Trump sentiment and a surge in progressive activism that led to the launch of the Squad into Congress and resulted in major primary losses for old-guard Democrats, including House Democrats chair Joe Crowley (Goldmacher and Martin (2018)). Protest data from that year reveals a diffuse but energetic left-wing mobilization: demonstrations targeted immigration (family separations), healthcare (ACA repeal attempts), and by a large margin, gun reform. The Backlash That Broke A Red Wave

Historical trends pointed to a Republican landslide in 2022: Bidens approval ratings languished, inflation soared, and midterms typically punish the incumbent party (Prokop (2022)). Yet the GOPs expected red wave collapsed, resulting in a razor-thin House majority and Democratic Senate gains. Protest data tells the story.

The Supreme Courts Dobbs decision (June 2022) triggered a seismic shift. Left-leaning protests exploded, with abortion rights becoming the dominant issue overnight. Figure 3 highlights the spike in abortion-related demonstrations post-Dobbs, which dwarfed right-wing activity.

Figure 3

Unlike 2018s scattered focus, 2022s protests were laser-targeted, galvanizing women and young voters. Swing states like Michigan and Pennsylvania saw record midterm turnout, with abortion ballot measures driving engagement. Meanwhile, right-wing mobilizationthough presentfailed to match the lefts intensity.

What about presidential years?

Extending the analysis to presidential cycles reveals nuances:

In 2020, the COVID-19 pandemic suppressed protest activity overall, but left-wing movements (e.g., racial justice protests after George Floyds killing) still dominated. The sole major right-leaning mobilization were anti-lockdown rallies. As we know, Democrats swept the election with the largest number of votes ever cast for a single candidate.

Figure 6

2020 Protest Issues

Figure 7

2024 data shows a notable rise in right-wing activity. While left-wing protests remain more frequent, there was a relative increase in conservative mobilization. With Republicans winning this election considerably, with a large swing towards Republicans (which is a result that should be taken with a grain of salt considering the large swing left in the 2020 election), the increases in right-leaning protest activity is acting like a predictor for Republican gains.

Figure 8

2024 Protest Issues

Figure 9

This aligns with my proposition: absolute left-wing dominance in protest numbers may not predict outcomes alone, but surges in right-wing activity could signal Republican electoral gains. One can also note that left-wing mobilization is nearly constant, while right-wing mobilization drops significantly when a Republican is an incumbent.

Limitations and Caveats

Two key caveats temper these insights. The data covers only 20172024, a period skewed toward Democratic overperformance in 3 of 4 federal elections. The data also includes multiple outlier election cycles that were unprecedented and rare in American history, with the COVID-19 pandemic raging on in 2020, and a presumptive nominee dropping out mid-cycle in 2024. Additionally, single-issue movements (e.g., abortion) may mobilize voters more effectively than diffuse grievances.

Why Protests Might Outperform Polls

Polls often lag behind real-time sentiment, but protests capture intensitya critical factor in voter turnout. Left-wing protests were consistently more numerous, but electoral impact depends on issue salience. On the other hand, right-Wing surges, even if smaller, may foreshadow GOP momentum. For analysts, tracking protest volume, valence, and issue focus could complement traditional metrics. This lays the groundwork for interesting insights, and with more historical data, we can determine the legitimacy of this theory.
